## Smart vs Dumb Components

### Dumb components (`src/components/`, `views/*/components/`, `*.ui.tsx`)

Dumb components are purely presentational. They receive props and render JSX.

ALLOWED:

- Local UI state (open/closed menus, accordions, tooltips, etc.)
- Handlers that update local UI state only
- Other dumb components
- Presentational-only contexts: i18n, theme, UI feature flags

FORBIDDEN:

- Calling services or making network requests
- Reading application contexts (user data, global business state)
- Including smart components
- Accepting data structures tightly coupled to the parent's implementation

```tsx
// ❌ DO NOT couple to parent state structure
const ToggleDisplay = ({
  displayInfo,
}: {
  displayInfo: [boolean, Dispatch<SetStateAction<boolean>>];
}) => {};

// ✅ Expose a clean, decoupled interface
const ToggleDisplay = ({
  open,
  onToggle,
}: {
  open: boolean;
  onToggle: () => void;
}) => {};
```

```tsx
// ❌ DO NOT include a smart component inside a dumb component
const UserListItem = ({ user }) => {
  const [isEditOpen, setIsEditOpen] = useState(false);
  return <>{isEditOpen && <EditUserDialog user={user} />}</>; // EditUserDialog is smart
};

// ✅ Lift state to the smart parent, pass a callback down
const UserListItem = ({ user, onEditClick }) => {
  return <button onClick={onEditClick}>Edit</button>;
};
```

### Smart components (`*.view.tsx`)

Smart components handle business logic: data fetching, side effects, error/loading states.

ALLOWED:

- Data fetching hooks (useQuery, useSWR, etc.)
- Application contexts
- Loading/error state management
- Passing data and callbacks to dumb components

FORBIDDEN:

- HTML markup (no JSX elements other than dumb component calls)
- Styles — no inline styles, no className

```tsx
// ❌ DO NOT put markup or styles in a smart component
const App = () => {
  return <div style={{ minHeight: "100vh" }}>{/* ... */}</div>;
};

// ✅ Delegate all presentation to a dumb component
const App = () => {
  return <Layout>{/* ... */}</Layout>;
};
```

