## Services vs Utils

|              | Services             | Utils                 |
| ------------ | -------------------- | --------------------- |
| Nature       | Async (I/O, network) | Sync (pure functions) |
| Side effects | Yes                  | None                  |
| Folder       | `services/`          | `utils/`              |

Services are always `async` or return a `Promise`.

```ts
// ✅ services/users.ts
export const fetchUsersUrl = '/api/users';
export async fetchUsers = (): Promise<User[]> => { ... }
```

Utils are always synchronous and pure. No API calls, no side effects.

```ts
// ✅ utils/format.ts
export truncate = (str: string, maxLength: number): string => { ... }
```

---

## Hooks

`hooks/` contains reusable React logic that is not UI.

- Hooks may call services
- Hooks must NOT return JSX
- View-specific hooks go in `views/<view>/hooks/`

---

## Code Scoping: Shared vs View-local

A file belongs in the **root** `src/` folders (`components/`, `utils/`, `services/`, etc.) only if it is used by **two or more views**.

If it is specific to a single view, it lives inside that view's folder.

```
src/
├── components/button/       ← used in multiple views → root
└── views/homescreen/
    ├── components/homescreen-hero/  ← only used here → view-local
    ├── utils/compute-stats.ts       ← only used here → view-local
    └── services/homescreen-data.ts  ← only used here → view-local
```

---

## Storybook

Every shared component in `src/components/` must have a `.stories.ts(x)` file documenting all its meaningful variants. We use `src/lrs-migration` as temporary folder for clean architecture files

```ts
// ✅ button.stories.ts
const meta: Meta<typeof Button> = { component: Button };
export default meta;

export const Primary: Story = {
  args: { variant: "primary", children: "Save" },
};
export const Danger: Story = {
  args: { variant: "danger", children: "Delete" },
};
export const Disabled: Story = {
  args: { variant: "primary", disabled: true, children: "Save" },
};
```

---

## Component Folder Structure

Every component (shared or view-local) lives in its own folder:

```
button/
├── button.stories.ts
├── button.tsx
└── index.ts              # public exports only
```

The `index.ts` exposes only the public API of the component. Internal sub-components are not re-exported.
